3 §3991.2. Vocational and technical education charter schools; enrollment
4 preferences; board membership
5 A. The legislature finds and declares that:
6 (1) The economic vitality of the state is dependent upon the education of
7 its people, including its current and future workforce.
8 (2) The performance of Louisiana's public education system is critical in
9 providing every Louisiana child with the ability to graduate, being equipped to
10 enter college or the workplace, in order to obtain a rewarding and self-
11 sustaining career and to contribute to society in meaningful ways.
12 (3) High-quality educational options are essential to the academic growth
13 of Louisiana's students and the ability of the state to expand existing businesses,
14 attract new businesses, and recruit and maintain a highly talented workforce.
15 (4) Manufacturing, industrial, technology, energy, utility, and other
16 sectors are all dependent on a workforce that has vocational training and
17 technical education.
18 (5) Providing students with access to classes or educational programs
19 directly aligned with high-demand and high-wage jobs will help provide
20 students with the experience and resources needed to help prepare them to be
21 effective employees and productive citizens.
22 (6) Encouraging and enhancing innovative vocational and technical
23 school curriculum models aligned with the state's workforce needs benefits the
24 state and its students.
25 B.(1) Notwithstanding geographic or other requirements for enrollment
26 contained in this Chapter, a charter agreement may provide, initially or by
27 amendment, for enrollment of students in a vocational and technical education
28 program.
29 (2)(a) Preference may be given to students whose parent or legal
30 guardian is employed or resides within the economic sector that is designated
